04374nam a22005895i 9780300168358DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20102010ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001683587 a10.12987/97803001683582doi  a(DE-B1597)486174  a(OCoLC)811405709  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aZ291.3 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a070.50941 aPettegree, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Book in the Renaissance /cAndrew Pettegree. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2010] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (448 p.) :b69 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPrelude -- t1. The Book Before Print -- t2. The Invention of Printing -- t3. Renaissance Encounters: The Crisis of Print -- t4. The Creation of a European Book Market -- t5. Book Town Wittenberg -- t6. Luther's Legacy -- t7. First with the News -- t8. Polite Recreations -- t9. At School -- t10. The Literature of Conflict -- t11. The Search for Order -- t12. Market Forces -- t13. Science and Exploration -- t14. Healing -- t15. Building a Library -- t16. Word and the Street -- tA Note on Sources: Mapping the Geography of Print -- tAppendix: A Summary of printed outputs throughout Europe, 1450-1600 -- tAcknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe dawn of print was a major turning point in the early modern world. It rescued ancient learning from obscurity, transformed knowledge of the natural and physical world, and brought the thrill of book ownership to the masses. But, as Andrew Pettegree reveals in this work of great historical merit, the story of the post-Gutenberg world was rather more complicated than we have often come to believe.The Book in the Renaissance reconstructs the first 150 years of the world of print, exploring the complex web of religious, economic, and cultural concerns surrounding the printed word. From its very beginnings, the printed book had to straddle financial and religious imperatives, as well as the very different requirements and constraints of the many countries who embraced it, and, as Pettegree argues, the process was far from a runaway success. More than ideas, the success or failure of books depended upon patrons and markets, precarious strategies and the thwarting of piracy, and the ebb and flow of popular demand. Owing to his state-of-the-art and highly detailed research, Pettegree crafts an authoritative, lucid, and truly pioneering work of cultural history about a major development in the evolution of European society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBook industries and tradezEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aBook industries and tradezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 0aBookszEuropexHistoryy1450-1600. 0aPrintingzEuropexHistoryxOrigin and antecedents. 0aPrintingzEuropexHistoryy16th century. 0aReformationzEurope. 0aRenaissance. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300168358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300168358.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles